  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called 'Epistemic Path Planner' (EPP), which reframes cross-document evidence retrieval as a hierarchical, uncertainty-guided decision process that dynamically fuses structured relational knowledge (e.g., hyperlinks, citation graphs) and unstructured factual knowledge (e.g., document text) through adaptive multi-hop reasoning. Unlike prior work that either predefines retrieval paths (Mr.Cod), uses static fusion (PILOT), or switches modalities via a fixed policy, EPP introduces a hierarchical reinforcement learning (HRL) agent that learns to interleave actions across modalities—such as 'retrieve semantically similar passage', 'follow outgoing hyperlink', or 'terminate and predict'—at each reasoning step. Crucially, each action is conditioned on an online estimate of epistemic uncertainty derived from ensemble disagreement over candidate relations, allowing the planner to adapt its strategy: under high uncertainty, it favors longer, more interpretable hyperlink chains that provide audit trails; under low uncertainty, it takes efficient semantic jumps using dense retrieval. The HRL agent consists of a top-level 'strategy selector' that decides the mode of exploration (graph vs. text) based on uncertainty and context, and a lower-level executor that implements the chosen action. Training occurs end-to-end using a reward function combining relation extraction F1, path fidelity (measured against human-annotated reasoning paths in CodRED), and path length (to encourage efficiency). During inference, EPP generates not only high-quality evidence sets but also interpretable, mixed-modal reasoning trajectories that can be audited and validated. This approach fundamentally advances dynamic fusion by treating it as a sequence of uncertainty-aware decisions rather than a single retrieval event. It addresses critical limitations in current systems: brittleness under distribution shift, lack of interpretability, and poor generalization to unseen relations. By enabling self-adjusting reasoning depth and modality use, EPP improves performance in challenging open-retrieval scenarios and offers a new paradigm for trustworthy, explainable AI in knowledge-intensive tasks.",
